 gender studies in three ways: by focusing on contemporary Black politics not only in the United States, but also the African Diaspora; by showcasing politics along a broad trajectory, including social movements, formal politics, public policy, media studies, and epistemology; and by including a multidisciplinary range of scholars, with a strong concentration of work by political scientists, a group whose work is often excluded or limited in edited collections. The final result expands our repertoire of methodological tools and concepts for discussing and assessing Black women's lives, the conditions under which they live, their labor, and the politics they enact to improve their circumstances.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aFeminismvCross-cultural studies. 0aWomen, BlackxPolitical activityvCross-cultural studies. 0aWomen, BlackxSocial conditionsvCross-cultural studies. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 4aPublic Policy : Public Policy. 4aSociology : Social Movements. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh1 aAlexander-Floyd, Nikol G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlexander-Floyd, Nikol G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBlain, Keisha N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDouglas, Jenny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, K. Melchor Quick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoward, Grace E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJordan-Zachery, Julia S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJordan-Zachery, Julia S., eeditor.4edt4h